00:00:09.812 --> 00:00:10.770
JESSE HAINES: So this--

00:00:10.770 --> 00:00:13.260
I loved reading this book.

00:00:13.260 --> 00:00:17.220
And definitely jumped into
this book with the perception

00:00:17.220 --> 00:00:19.830
that I think many
folks might have,

00:00:19.830 --> 00:00:23.790
that the gig economy is
this great thing that

00:00:23.790 --> 00:00:25.950
allows everybody to
be their own boss,

00:00:25.950 --> 00:00:29.999
and play by their own
rules and so forth.

00:00:29.999 --> 00:00:32.040
And I think what you have
done so powerfully here

00:00:32.040 --> 00:00:35.260
is really kind of unpack that.

00:00:35.260 --> 00:00:37.560
But why don't we, just
to kick things off,

00:00:37.560 --> 00:00:39.400
start with the basics?

00:00:39.400 --> 00:00:42.240
What is the gig economy?

00:00:42.240 --> 00:00:44.790
SARAH KESSLER: So that is a
surprisingly controversial

00:00:44.790 --> 00:00:45.570
question.

00:00:45.570 --> 00:00:48.210
People will fight
about this for hours.

00:00:48.210 --> 00:00:51.600
Because some people
think that gig economy is

00:00:51.600 --> 00:00:57.060
only kind of apps that
give out jobs, like Uber.

00:00:57.060 --> 00:00:59.400
Some people think
it's all freelancers.

00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:02.400
Some people think it's
kind of this shift away

00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:04.590
from full-time employment,
whether that be

00:01:04.590 --> 00:01:07.320
contract workers
or temp workers,

00:01:07.320 --> 00:01:10.630
or other things that
aren't traditional jobs.

00:01:10.630 --> 00:01:13.710
I think it's kind of
just a buzzword used

00:01:13.710 --> 00:01:17.940
to describe these set of
companies that came up

00:01:17.940 --> 00:01:20.750
with this new idea
of-- well, let's say

00:01:20.750 --> 00:01:22.720
[INAUDIBLE] was a new idea.

00:01:22.720 --> 00:01:26.820
We can control independent
work through an app.

00:01:26.820 --> 00:01:29.610
In the book, I was looking
at how does technology

00:01:29.610 --> 00:01:32.540
impact this long-term trend
towards freelance workers?

00:01:32.540 --> 00:01:34.290
JESSE HAINES: Definitely
a little bit more

00:01:34.290 --> 00:01:40.020
controversial than you
would have thought.

00:01:40.020 --> 00:01:45.035
So maybe let's dig in on that
technology piece a little bit.

00:01:45.035 --> 00:01:53.220
So how have all the advances
that we've seen in technology

00:01:53.220 --> 00:01:56.554
impacted the gigging culture?

00:01:56.554 --> 00:01:57.720
SARAH KESSLER: So let's see.

00:01:57.720 --> 00:02:00.300
I started getting
introduced to this topic,

00:02:00.300 --> 00:02:03.600
and started looking at it
when I was a tech blogger,

00:02:03.600 --> 00:02:06.270
and I was hearing three
to four startups a day

00:02:06.270 --> 00:02:08.310
pitch me their companies.

00:02:08.310 --> 00:02:11.980
Maybe there are three or four
of those still around today.

00:02:11.980 --> 00:02:13.970
That was in 2010.

00:02:13.970 --> 00:02:16.830
And I noticed this pattern of
pitch, which went something

00:02:16.830 --> 00:02:19.200
like, hey, we've
created this app that's

00:02:19.200 --> 00:02:20.640
going to solve unemployment.

00:02:20.640 --> 00:02:23.350
Because in 2010, that
was still a problem.

00:02:23.350 --> 00:02:26.350
And it's also going to make
everybody love their jobs.

00:02:26.350 --> 00:02:27.210
It's called Uber.

00:02:27.210 --> 00:02:29.760
It's called Uber for car
washing or it's called Uber

00:02:29.760 --> 00:02:31.620
for brushing your teeth--

00:02:31.620 --> 00:02:33.019
whatever.

00:02:33.019 --> 00:02:34.560
But now, you can
just press a button.

00:02:34.560 --> 00:02:35.460
You can get work.

00:02:35.460 --> 00:02:36.270
Problem solved.

00:02:36.270 --> 00:02:38.740
You're welcome.

00:02:38.740 --> 00:02:42.690
And I think as that played
out-- and in the book,

00:02:42.690 --> 00:02:47.760
I follow people in very
different positions

00:02:47.760 --> 00:02:51.690
within that world, and
how it plays out for them.

00:02:51.690 --> 00:02:57.030
But they found ways to take what
had been a totally independent,

00:02:57.030 --> 00:03:00.450
"I'm my own business," which is
something that totally exists.

00:03:00.450 --> 00:03:05.400
And really is that great,
work-from-the-beach situation.

00:03:05.400 --> 00:03:08.359
But they found a way to make
it the same classification

00:03:08.359 --> 00:03:10.400
and still give people the
responsibility of being

00:03:10.400 --> 00:03:13.110
your own business, but
actually, in reality,

00:03:13.110 --> 00:03:15.220
manage you a little bit.

00:03:15.220 --> 00:03:17.610
It's also much easier
to hire a freelancer

00:03:17.610 --> 00:03:18.750
than it's ever been before.

00:03:18.750 --> 00:03:20.310
There are these
online platforms.

00:03:20.310 --> 00:03:23.400
There's easy ways to search.

00:03:23.400 --> 00:03:24.949
You can keep track of them.

00:03:24.949 --> 00:03:26.490
Some of these
platforms have features

00:03:26.490 --> 00:03:28.140
where, if you hire
a freelancer, you

00:03:28.140 --> 00:03:30.784
can also watch a
video of all the hours

00:03:30.784 --> 00:03:32.700
that they are working
for you on their desktop

00:03:32.700 --> 00:03:34.650
to make sure that they
didn't check their email

00:03:34.650 --> 00:03:37.149
or something while they were
supposed to be working for you.

00:03:37.149 --> 00:03:39.540
So there are all these
things that make it easier.

00:03:39.540 --> 00:03:43.890
And while this has been a
shift since the '70s, companies

00:03:43.890 --> 00:03:46.140
outsourcing more and
more of their work

00:03:46.140 --> 00:03:48.970
out to people who
aren't their employees,

00:03:48.970 --> 00:03:52.305
I think that technology makes
it easier in more situations.

00:03:52.305 --> 00:03:54.180
JESSE HAINES: What I
love most about the book

00:03:54.180 --> 00:03:58.710
is that you brought us
into the gig economy

00:03:58.710 --> 00:04:04.050
through stories of individuals
who are all interacting

00:04:04.050 --> 00:04:07.800
in very different ways with--

00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:10.210
participating in the gig
economy in very different ways.

00:04:10.210 --> 00:04:18.209
So let's dig in a little bit
to some of those stories.

00:04:18.209 --> 00:04:20.550
And I'll let you decide.

00:04:20.550 --> 00:04:22.950
The takeaway, I
think, for me, was

00:04:22.950 --> 00:04:25.860
that there's a lot to offer.

00:04:25.860 --> 00:04:28.030
Some are thriving, some are not.

00:04:28.030 --> 00:04:33.990
And there's just a lot
more nuance and challenges

00:04:33.990 --> 00:04:35.700
in this gig economy.

00:04:35.700 --> 00:04:39.180
So tell us about--

00:04:39.180 --> 00:04:41.130
maybe start with
someone who's thriving.

00:04:41.130 --> 00:04:42.690
Tell us about Curtis.

00:04:42.690 --> 00:04:43.440
SARAH KESSLER: OK.

00:04:43.440 --> 00:04:47.890
So Curtis is a
software programmer.

00:04:47.890 --> 00:04:50.400
He just graduated from college.

00:04:50.400 --> 00:04:55.290
He went to work his full-time
job for the first time,

00:04:55.290 --> 00:04:57.410
and realized it
was super boring.

00:04:57.410 --> 00:05:00.180
He was done with his work at
noon, and he had nothing to do.

00:05:00.180 --> 00:05:03.330
So he watched people play
video games on the internet,

00:05:03.330 --> 00:05:06.250
and tried to pitch projects,
but they went nowhere.

00:05:06.250 --> 00:05:10.390
So he was extremely
frustrated and bored,

00:05:10.390 --> 00:05:11.620
and was looking for jobs.

00:05:11.620 --> 00:05:14.380
And ran across this
platform called

00:05:14.380 --> 00:05:20.170
Gigster, which doles
out freelance jobs

00:05:20.170 --> 00:05:24.340
to independent contractors
who are software developers.

00:05:24.340 --> 00:05:29.920
And he quit his job, joined
this, and in his first month,

00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:32.200
made $12,000.

00:05:32.200 --> 00:05:34.984
Didn't have to go out and
find clients, or advertise,

00:05:34.984 --> 00:05:37.150
or do any of the things
that are normally associated

00:05:37.150 --> 00:05:39.010
with a small business.

00:05:39.010 --> 00:05:40.420
Totally loved it.

00:05:40.420 --> 00:05:43.150
Got to pick his own projects,
grew as an employee.

00:05:43.150 --> 00:05:45.580
And then, ended up
leaving the gig economy

00:05:45.580 --> 00:05:48.160
because he had built
his resume enough

00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:53.225
where he was able to land his
dream job, which was at SpaceX.

00:05:56.830 --> 00:05:59.845
JESSE HAINES: So that's kind of,
I think, maybe a little bit--

00:05:59.845 --> 00:06:00.720
SARAH KESSLER: Right.

00:06:00.720 --> 00:06:01.600
That's the happy side.

00:06:01.600 --> 00:06:03.183
JESSE HAINES: --the
gig economy dream.

00:06:03.183 --> 00:06:05.170
But there were a
lot of other stories

00:06:05.170 --> 00:06:09.760
that didn't quite
turn out like that.

00:06:09.760 --> 00:06:12.430
So tell us about another person.

00:06:12.430 --> 00:06:13.760
SARAH KESSLER: Sure.

00:06:13.760 --> 00:06:19.450
So Curtis's situation was
a specific, highly skilled

00:06:19.450 --> 00:06:20.780
professional situation.

00:06:20.780 --> 00:06:22.480
And I think a lot
of what's happened

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:26.350
is people who are
promoting this kind of work

00:06:26.350 --> 00:06:28.960
for work that's not that have
taken that narrative and said,

00:06:28.960 --> 00:06:31.626
that's what it's like for, also,
these people who are giving you

00:06:31.626 --> 00:06:35.170
rides, or fixing your scooters,
or whatever it is that is not

00:06:35.170 --> 00:06:39.820
highly paid, professional
work, which is not necessarily

00:06:39.820 --> 00:06:40.610
the case.

00:06:40.610 --> 00:06:44.350
So before Curtis quit
to join the gig economy,

00:06:44.350 --> 00:06:47.497
he saved a year's worth
of living expenses.

00:06:47.497 --> 00:06:49.330
He met with an accountant
to see how much he

00:06:49.330 --> 00:06:53.230
had to save for taxes,
and what else did he do?

00:06:53.230 --> 00:06:54.940
He bought health insurance.

00:06:54.940 --> 00:06:58.150
So he kind of created this
social safety net for himself.

00:06:58.150 --> 00:07:01.780
You know, if he got called
to jury duty, which he did,

00:07:01.780 --> 00:07:04.200
and he couldn't work, he
just moved his projects

00:07:04.200 --> 00:07:05.410
to the next week, you know?

00:07:05.410 --> 00:07:07.520
It wasn't like he
couldn't buy groceries.

00:07:07.520 --> 00:07:11.240
So for other people in
these situations, where,

00:07:11.240 --> 00:07:13.010
when you're working
as a freelancer,

00:07:13.010 --> 00:07:16.930
you don't have any protections
from any labor laws.

00:07:16.930 --> 00:07:19.930
Not even discrimination
or sexual harassment.

00:07:19.930 --> 00:07:22.270
You have no minimum wage.

00:07:22.270 --> 00:07:25.990
No right to unionize,
which is a big one.

00:07:25.990 --> 00:07:27.700
And that's a much
bigger problem if you

00:07:27.700 --> 00:07:31.090
don't have the power of a
year's worth of savings.

00:07:31.090 --> 00:07:36.040
So there was this other
project in rural Arkansas,

00:07:36.040 --> 00:07:38.230
where a nonprofit
heard this pitch

00:07:38.230 --> 00:07:41.692
about if opportunity
isn't around you,

00:07:41.692 --> 00:07:43.150
you can just press
a button and you

00:07:43.150 --> 00:07:45.820
can get connected
with these gigs

00:07:45.820 --> 00:07:48.220
and have instant employment.

00:07:48.220 --> 00:07:51.250
And they thought, we'll take
to rural Arkansas, where

00:07:51.250 --> 00:07:53.350
the normal workforce
development thing to do

00:07:53.350 --> 00:07:57.400
is build businesses, attract
businesses to give jobs.

00:07:57.400 --> 00:08:01.390
But instead, we'll teach people
how to use the gig economy.

00:08:01.390 --> 00:08:03.890
And they'll get jobs that way.

00:08:03.890 --> 00:08:07.450
So I followed this project
for two or three years.

00:08:07.450 --> 00:08:13.990
And the false thinking
of "we can make an app

00:08:13.990 --> 00:08:15.910
that fixes this
problem" became very

00:08:15.910 --> 00:08:18.150
apparent very
quickly to everyone

00:08:18.150 --> 00:08:19.630
who was involved in it.

00:08:23.170 --> 00:08:25.690
It works if you're a programmer
to just download an app

00:08:25.690 --> 00:08:26.530
and use your skills.

00:08:26.530 --> 00:08:30.120
But that's not the problem
for people who are--

00:08:30.120 --> 00:08:33.549
40% of whom are living in
poverty in this small town.

00:08:33.549 --> 00:08:36.820
They don't have high-speed
internet that works.

00:08:36.820 --> 00:08:39.549
They don't have educations
that allow them to get jobs,

00:08:39.549 --> 00:08:42.520
like social media
consultant, where

00:08:42.520 --> 00:08:47.380
you need perfect grammar to
be able to gracefully meld

00:08:47.380 --> 00:08:51.010
a sale into a punchy joke.

00:08:51.010 --> 00:08:54.010
So they just ended up
applying and applying and not

00:08:54.010 --> 00:08:54.770
getting anywhere.

00:08:54.770 --> 00:08:56.680
And I think, at the
end of the program,

00:08:56.680 --> 00:08:59.500
there was something like
over four years, four

00:08:59.500 --> 00:09:03.190
people had gotten
any work, one of whom

00:09:03.190 --> 00:09:04.990
I actually follow in this book.

00:09:04.990 --> 00:09:06.282
And you can cut me off if I'm--

00:09:06.282 --> 00:09:07.406
JESSE HAINES: Yeah, no, no.

00:09:07.406 --> 00:09:08.870
I think this is interesting.

00:09:08.870 --> 00:09:12.340
SARAH KESSLER: But the
man from the program,

00:09:12.340 --> 00:09:17.110
who I followed in the book,
his name is Gary Foster.

00:09:17.110 --> 00:09:20.320
And the digital job he got
was as a customer service

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:22.180
representative for Sears.

00:09:22.180 --> 00:09:23.020
You remember Sears.

00:09:23.020 --> 00:09:24.298
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:25.150 --> 00:09:28.430
And so his relationship
to Sears was--

00:09:28.430 --> 00:09:30.130
he would pick up
the phone, be like,

00:09:30.130 --> 00:09:32.710
thanks for calling
customer service at Sears.

00:09:32.710 --> 00:09:36.370
He was an independent
contractor to a small business.

00:09:36.370 --> 00:09:40.570
And that small business had
a contract with a call center

00:09:40.570 --> 00:09:42.880
that had a contract with Sears.

00:09:42.880 --> 00:09:46.480
So that's a lot of
layers, to the point

00:09:46.480 --> 00:09:48.020
where, if something
happens to him,

00:09:48.020 --> 00:09:49.360
Sears is not going
to be like, oh, yeah.

00:09:49.360 --> 00:09:50.276
That was our employee.

00:09:50.276 --> 00:09:52.840
They're going to be like, I
don't know who that guy is.

00:09:52.840 --> 00:09:54.550
He had questions
about his check,

00:09:54.550 --> 00:09:57.220
and he was afraid
to say anything

00:09:57.220 --> 00:09:59.800
because he knew that there
was nothing protecting him

00:09:59.800 --> 00:10:01.750
from wrongful termination.

00:10:01.750 --> 00:10:06.750
And then, when they required
him to take a three-week class

00:10:06.750 --> 00:10:09.840
to train, which his instructor
had negotiated that he wouldn't

00:10:09.840 --> 00:10:10.740
have to pay for.

00:10:10.740 --> 00:10:13.950
Because, usually, you would
have to pay for the training

00:10:13.950 --> 00:10:18.180
class for three weeks that you
would take in order to work.

00:10:18.180 --> 00:10:21.690
But he wasn't making
any money, and so he

00:10:21.690 --> 00:10:24.510
wasn't paying his bills.

00:10:24.510 --> 00:10:27.180
There's also a
questionable flexibility

00:10:27.180 --> 00:10:29.830
because the pitch is you
can work whenever you want.

00:10:29.830 --> 00:10:32.520
But if you're doing something
like customer service, how

00:10:32.520 --> 00:10:36.270
you get hours is whenever
they have hours available.

00:10:36.270 --> 00:10:38.977
And so they release the
hours onto this platform,

00:10:38.977 --> 00:10:40.560
and everyone scrambles
to pick them up

00:10:40.560 --> 00:10:43.360
as quick as they can
anytime they're available.

00:10:43.360 --> 00:10:48.690
So if that's 20 hours
this week, that's great.

00:10:48.690 --> 00:10:51.420
It might only be four, and
you didn't get another job

00:10:51.420 --> 00:10:55.900
because you thought you
were going to work 20.

00:10:55.900 --> 00:10:59.730
JESSE HAINES: So I think
this rural Arkansas example

00:10:59.730 --> 00:11:05.010
definitely highlighted
certainly a lot of the pitfalls

00:11:05.010 --> 00:11:06.690
and challenges of
the gig economy.

00:11:06.690 --> 00:11:13.840
But I think Terrence,
who was the guy who said,

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:14.830
let's give this a try.

00:11:14.830 --> 00:11:17.910
Let's see if I can
make this gig thing

00:11:17.910 --> 00:11:25.260
work in my small, rural hometown
that is challenged, and is

00:11:25.260 --> 00:11:27.540
on such hard times.

00:11:27.540 --> 00:11:29.790
Do you think there's any hope?

00:11:29.790 --> 00:11:32.910
Did you walk away
from that saying, no,

00:11:32.910 --> 00:11:35.355
this is just never
going to be able to--

00:11:35.355 --> 00:11:37.330
this is great for the
Curtises of the world,

00:11:37.330 --> 00:11:41.370
but not for small, rural
towns where there just

00:11:41.370 --> 00:11:42.690
aren't enough jobs?

00:11:42.690 --> 00:11:44.440
SARAH KESSLER: I think
it could be better.

00:11:46.802 --> 00:11:48.510
The fact that we've
structured everything

00:11:48.510 --> 00:11:52.500
around this 9:00 to 5:00 job,
there's a lot of flaws in that.

00:11:52.500 --> 00:11:55.140
It was kind of built
for a time when

00:11:55.140 --> 00:11:57.405
we thought an ideal
family meant a man that

00:11:57.405 --> 00:11:59.940
goes to work all day, and a
woman who stays home and works

00:11:59.940 --> 00:12:01.354
all day for free.

00:12:01.354 --> 00:12:03.270
And to the extent that
that was ever the case,

00:12:03.270 --> 00:12:06.040
that is very much
no longer the case.

00:12:06.040 --> 00:12:08.130
And that causes-- this
idea everyone should

00:12:08.130 --> 00:12:11.250
work on the same schedule
causes a lot of families a lot

00:12:11.250 --> 00:12:12.960
of stress.

00:12:12.960 --> 00:12:17.910
You have people who are going
to school or doing other things

00:12:17.910 --> 00:12:20.250
that they want to work
less than full time.

00:12:20.250 --> 00:12:23.130
People are living
longer and healthier.

00:12:23.130 --> 00:12:24.270
And maybe they don't--

00:12:24.270 --> 00:12:26.327
if they're going to have
a 60-year long career,

00:12:26.327 --> 00:12:28.410
don't want to work full-time
for that whole thing.

00:12:28.410 --> 00:12:32.640
So there are definitely
potentials for this.

00:12:32.640 --> 00:12:36.030
Also, the need to work
that way, technology

00:12:36.030 --> 00:12:37.780
is taking away a
little bit, too.

00:12:37.780 --> 00:12:41.880
You don't have to come to
the office to get the files,

00:12:41.880 --> 00:12:44.731
or to talk to people
you're working with.

00:12:44.731 --> 00:12:46.230
More and more of
the country doesn't

00:12:46.230 --> 00:12:50.635
have to go to work to
be in the assembly line.

00:12:50.635 --> 00:12:51.760
There's a lot of potential.

00:12:51.760 --> 00:12:55.260
It's just all of our structure
is around this 9:00 to 5:00

00:12:55.260 --> 00:12:57.090
job.

00:12:57.090 --> 00:12:59.070
So when that was
created, which was

00:12:59.070 --> 00:13:03.000
a new thing at the time in
the Industrial Revolution,

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:08.700
coming from being distributed on
farms, we screwed up at first.

00:13:08.700 --> 00:13:10.320
We sent children to work.

00:13:10.320 --> 00:13:14.130
We locked people inside of
factories that might burn down.

00:13:14.130 --> 00:13:17.280
It was bad, but then we
developed these structures--

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:22.490
like labor laws and
social benefits--

00:13:22.490 --> 00:13:23.920
that supported it.

00:13:23.920 --> 00:13:27.490
And just don't have that at
all for this kind of work.

00:13:27.490 --> 00:13:30.690
JESSE HAINES: So let's stay
on that for a little while.

00:13:30.690 --> 00:13:32.175
Where do you think--

00:13:35.460 --> 00:13:36.930
the gig economy is marching on.

00:13:36.930 --> 00:13:38.120
It's just growing.

00:13:38.120 --> 00:13:40.110
All the data would
point to the fact

00:13:40.110 --> 00:13:45.420
that this phenomenon is just
getting bigger and bigger.

00:13:45.420 --> 00:13:48.760
And now, policy needs
to kind of catch up.

00:13:48.760 --> 00:13:51.060
What are your thoughts
on some of the things

00:13:51.060 --> 00:13:54.277
that we need in that area?

00:13:54.277 --> 00:13:55.110
SARAH KESSLER: Sure.

00:13:55.110 --> 00:13:57.657
So this is something that
I think is interesting.

00:13:57.657 --> 00:13:59.490
Because when you talk
about the gig economy,

00:13:59.490 --> 00:14:00.989
depending on your
definition, you're

00:14:00.989 --> 00:14:05.110
talking about a
small set of people.

00:14:05.110 --> 00:14:06.980
But here's a place,
I think, where

00:14:06.980 --> 00:14:08.790
if you solved some
of their problems,

00:14:08.790 --> 00:14:11.680
you would solve other
people's problems, as well.

00:14:11.680 --> 00:14:13.770
So for instance, there's
a lot of employees

00:14:13.770 --> 00:14:16.950
who are paying more and more
for health insurance provided

00:14:16.950 --> 00:14:20.010
by their companies,
even, every year.

00:14:20.010 --> 00:14:26.340
Or their retirement savings
or 401(k)s with the company

00:14:26.340 --> 00:14:28.380
instead of pensions.

00:14:28.380 --> 00:14:31.530
And they're accepting more
risk, and also feeling

00:14:31.530 --> 00:14:33.220
tied to the company.

00:14:33.220 --> 00:14:38.040
So the big idea for how to
solve the gig economy's problems

00:14:38.040 --> 00:14:40.500
is benefits should be portable.

00:14:40.500 --> 00:14:43.110
Either everyone should
have health insurance,

00:14:43.110 --> 00:14:48.010
or your health insurance
shouldn't be tied to your job.

00:14:48.010 --> 00:14:50.730
Maybe multiple employers
can pay into it.

00:14:50.730 --> 00:14:57.000
Maybe it's housed with a
union or another entity.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:00.330
And so I think that's kind
of the leading idea for how

00:15:00.330 --> 00:15:03.030
to make things better.

00:15:03.030 --> 00:15:06.940
And the problem is everyone can
agree that that's a good idea,

00:15:06.940 --> 00:15:10.030
but they all mean totally
different things when

00:15:10.030 --> 00:15:12.640
they say that it's a good
idea about who pays for it

00:15:12.640 --> 00:15:15.220
and those kind of things.

00:15:15.220 --> 00:15:16.810
JESSE HAINES: Yeah, yeah.

00:15:16.810 --> 00:15:19.360
Have you seen any
interesting developments,

00:15:19.360 --> 00:15:25.837
or any progress against any
of the ideas to support this?

00:15:25.837 --> 00:15:26.670
SARAH KESSLER: Yeah.

00:15:26.670 --> 00:15:29.980
There's a group of
Democrats in the House

00:15:29.980 --> 00:15:33.130
that are campaigning
for this idea.

00:15:33.130 --> 00:15:35.980
But again, short
on details, which

00:15:35.980 --> 00:15:38.320
is really where it
needs to be worked out.

00:15:38.320 --> 00:15:41.050
A union leader will
say, what we mean

00:15:41.050 --> 00:15:43.360
is everyone will have
a $15 minimum wage.

00:15:43.360 --> 00:15:45.460
Everyone will have
a full pension.

00:15:45.460 --> 00:15:48.010
And then you get the other
side, which is like, great.

00:15:48.010 --> 00:15:51.610
Companies will pay for
nothing, and good luck.

00:15:51.610 --> 00:15:53.980
But we both support
portable benefits.

00:15:53.980 --> 00:15:57.520
So few details on that.

00:15:57.520 --> 00:16:02.495
One thing I think is
interesting is the idea of--

00:16:02.495 --> 00:16:04.870
I really think that these are
structural problems that we

00:16:04.870 --> 00:16:07.850
need to solve with policy.

00:16:07.850 --> 00:16:10.300
But one interesting
idea, aside from that,

00:16:10.300 --> 00:16:14.780
is having cooperatively-owned
platforms.

00:16:14.780 --> 00:16:21.250
So if your Uber driver
owned part of the Uber app,

00:16:21.250 --> 00:16:23.890
they would benefit from
this new efficiency

00:16:23.890 --> 00:16:27.340
that they're creating by
participating in Uber.

00:16:27.340 --> 00:16:31.060
And the same thing that
makes it easy for Uber

00:16:31.060 --> 00:16:33.010
to manage freelancers
in this way

00:16:33.010 --> 00:16:35.770
could make a co-op
a lot easier, too.

00:16:35.770 --> 00:16:39.149
Like software scales.

00:16:39.149 --> 00:16:40.690
If I'm going to
start a new Uber app,

00:16:40.690 --> 00:16:46.630
I can buy a white label
solution for, like, $30 a month.

00:16:46.630 --> 00:16:49.270
And everybody knows what a white
label solution is here, right?

00:16:49.270 --> 00:16:52.000
Because I'm in Google.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:56.050
And if I want people
to vote on everything

00:16:56.050 --> 00:16:57.610
I'm doing in the
co-op, I don't have

00:16:57.610 --> 00:17:00.470
to go door to door
with my ballot.

00:17:00.470 --> 00:17:02.470
I can send them a
push notification.

00:17:02.470 --> 00:17:06.099
So I think there's some
promise in that idea.

00:17:06.099 --> 00:17:07.990
JESSE HAINES: Interesting.

00:17:07.990 --> 00:17:11.290
Getting back to the book for
just a second, another story

00:17:11.290 --> 00:17:13.960
that I thought would
be interesting to share

00:17:13.960 --> 00:17:16.940
with the group is the
story of Christie,

00:17:16.940 --> 00:17:20.890
who I think was able to really
benefit from the gig economy,

00:17:20.890 --> 00:17:24.849
but not without some
tough consequences.

00:17:24.849 --> 00:17:27.670
Can you share her story
with the folks here?

00:17:27.670 --> 00:17:28.910
SARAH KESSLER: Sure.

00:17:28.910 --> 00:17:32.290
So I think she's a good
example of, in some ways,

00:17:32.290 --> 00:17:36.850
being a good thing that there's
this opportunity that exists.

00:17:36.850 --> 00:17:40.580
But also still, at the same
time, maybe not super fair,

00:17:40.580 --> 00:17:44.050
something we can
be too proud of.

00:17:44.050 --> 00:17:46.480
How many of what
Mechanical Turk is?

00:17:46.480 --> 00:17:48.340
Amazon Mechanical Turk?

00:17:48.340 --> 00:17:49.330
Everyone?

00:17:49.330 --> 00:17:50.580
JESSE HAINES: A lot of people.

00:17:50.580 --> 00:17:52.400
SARAH KESSLER: OK, awesome.

00:17:52.400 --> 00:17:56.534
So Christie, back
during the recession--

00:17:56.534 --> 00:17:58.200
JESSE HAINES: I would
explain it anyway.

00:17:58.200 --> 00:17:59.991
There might be some--
not all the hands on.

00:17:59.991 --> 00:18:01.010
SARAH KESSLER: OK.

00:18:01.010 --> 00:18:05.020
So Amazon Mechanical Turk is
this platform where companies

00:18:05.020 --> 00:18:08.590
can post small tasks, and
then thousands of people

00:18:08.590 --> 00:18:14.410
pick them up and do them for
maybe $0.05 or less a task.

00:18:14.410 --> 00:18:17.730
An example might be like,
I have 1,000 products

00:18:17.730 --> 00:18:19.900
on my e-commerce site.

00:18:19.900 --> 00:18:22.180
Label each one every time you--

00:18:22.180 --> 00:18:23.680
or write a description
for each one.

00:18:23.680 --> 00:18:27.120
Every time you do
that, you win $0.05.

00:18:27.120 --> 00:18:30.520
Or another very common
thing that happens

00:18:30.520 --> 00:18:34.510
is, label these
images which they're

00:18:34.510 --> 00:18:40.872
creating data for machine
learning algorithms, which I--

00:18:40.872 --> 00:18:43.330
do I need to explain machine
learning algorithms to Google?

00:18:43.330 --> 00:18:44.260
JESSE HAINES: I think that
maybe we're good on that.

00:18:44.260 --> 00:18:46.135
SARAH KESSLER: I feel
like you guys got that.

00:18:46.135 --> 00:18:47.649
All right.

00:18:47.649 --> 00:18:49.565
Usually, I have to spend
10 minutes explaining

00:18:49.565 --> 00:18:50.370
what that is.

00:18:50.370 --> 00:18:53.080
This is kind of fun.

00:18:53.080 --> 00:18:57.340
So Christie, her husband
lost his job in a factory.

00:18:57.340 --> 00:18:58.870
She realized she
has to make money.

00:18:58.870 --> 00:19:01.630
She's never worked outside
the home before, really.

00:19:01.630 --> 00:19:03.040
She has no resume.

00:19:03.040 --> 00:19:04.450
She's applied at McDonald's.

00:19:04.450 --> 00:19:06.580
They haven't called her back.

00:19:06.580 --> 00:19:09.430
So she logs onto
Amazon Mechanical Turk.

00:19:09.430 --> 00:19:13.900
And because she is a genius,
makes $40,000 a year,

00:19:13.900 --> 00:19:16.360
$0.05 at a time.

00:19:16.360 --> 00:19:18.550
And the way that she
does this involves

00:19:18.550 --> 00:19:24.110
all sorts of really
entrepreneurial thinking.

00:19:24.110 --> 00:19:26.830
She set up-- there
was a forum where

00:19:26.830 --> 00:19:29.440
people on Amazon
Mechanical Turk alert

00:19:29.440 --> 00:19:33.490
each other of good jobs, which
are ones that you can repeat

00:19:33.490 --> 00:19:35.530
really fast, that pay well.

00:19:35.530 --> 00:19:37.997
And she had an alarm on her
computer that would go off--

00:19:37.997 --> 00:19:38.830
JESSE HAINES: Crazy.

00:19:38.830 --> 00:19:40.240
SARAH KESSLER: --if
someone posted there,

00:19:40.240 --> 00:19:41.980
after they checked
if she was qualified

00:19:41.980 --> 00:19:43.390
and could do the task.

00:19:43.390 --> 00:19:47.780
And it had different levels of
alarm for how good the job was.

00:19:47.780 --> 00:19:50.260
And she would sleep
in her office in case

00:19:50.260 --> 00:19:54.110
the alarm went off, and
she could do this quickly.

00:19:54.110 --> 00:19:55.850
So all sorts of
things like that.

00:19:55.850 --> 00:19:57.700
And so she did it.

00:19:57.700 --> 00:20:00.520
She made the ends meet.

00:20:00.520 --> 00:20:02.590
But after a while,
you don't want

00:20:02.590 --> 00:20:06.950
to be sleeping in your office
and jumping up for an alarm.

00:20:06.950 --> 00:20:11.720
She developed a lot of injuries
in her wrists and shoulders,

00:20:11.720 --> 00:20:14.270
from literally sitting
at the computer.

00:20:14.270 --> 00:20:16.658
Most of this work is very--

00:20:16.658 --> 00:20:18.650
you have to use a
lot of keystrokes

00:20:18.650 --> 00:20:22.550
and a lot of mouse work, and
there's no workers compensation

00:20:22.550 --> 00:20:23.600
insurance.

00:20:23.600 --> 00:20:25.230
So even though her
job had hurt her,

00:20:25.230 --> 00:20:27.020
she had to keep
working through it.

00:20:27.020 --> 00:20:31.530
She couldn't afford the
medication, to get surgery.

00:20:31.530 --> 00:20:34.350
So it was just, for me, this--

00:20:34.350 --> 00:20:36.620
OK, great.

00:20:36.620 --> 00:20:37.864
There was this opportunity.

00:20:37.864 --> 00:20:40.280
I don't know how you would
have made this money otherwise.

00:20:40.280 --> 00:20:43.150
But also, maybe we can
do better than this.

00:20:43.150 --> 00:20:44.279
Yeah.

00:20:44.279 --> 00:20:45.070
JESSE HAINES: Yeah.

00:20:45.070 --> 00:20:48.240
A fascinating story of Christie.

00:20:48.240 --> 00:20:50.730
Let's zoom out a little bit.

00:20:50.730 --> 00:20:52.380
You've shared some
ideas of how you

00:20:52.380 --> 00:20:55.350
think you could make gig work
a little bit more secure.

00:20:55.350 --> 00:21:00.220
What about-- how is the gig
economy impacting our culture?

00:21:00.220 --> 00:21:02.040
SARAH KESSLER:
That's interesting.

00:21:02.040 --> 00:21:06.270
I think this break away
from directly employing

00:21:06.270 --> 00:21:09.570
your janitor and your bus driver
and everything, that's been

00:21:09.570 --> 00:21:11.700
in the works for a long time.

00:21:11.700 --> 00:21:15.030
A lot of these apps that are
a part of the gig economy

00:21:15.030 --> 00:21:17.490
are also part of the
on-demand economy.

00:21:17.490 --> 00:21:21.510
And certainly, there's a
new immediacy with which

00:21:21.510 --> 00:21:23.620
people expect certain things--

00:21:23.620 --> 00:21:27.210
or certain people
expect certain things.

00:21:27.210 --> 00:21:33.560
And then, people talk about this
surf culture in San Francisco

00:21:33.560 --> 00:21:35.400
when they talk about
the gig economy.

00:21:35.400 --> 00:21:37.410
JESSE HAINES: What
does that mean?

00:21:37.410 --> 00:21:39.690
SARAH KESSLER: You have the
people who make the apps

00:21:39.690 --> 00:21:45.120
and the people who work for
the apps, and it's become--

00:21:45.120 --> 00:21:48.210
partly because of
this labor system,

00:21:48.210 --> 00:21:50.700
where labor is so
cheap, and also you only

00:21:50.700 --> 00:21:54.240
pay for exactly
how much you use,

00:21:54.240 --> 00:21:59.520
it's never been less expensive
to have a personal driver

00:21:59.520 --> 00:22:02.490
and someone who you can
press a button on your phone,

00:22:02.490 --> 00:22:03.900
and they'll come do your hair.

00:22:03.900 --> 00:22:12.240
And it almost echoes this
royalty-feudal system

00:22:12.240 --> 00:22:16.620
that we thought was something
for historical drama.

00:22:16.620 --> 00:22:19.080
I'm a big "Downton Abbey" fan.

00:22:19.080 --> 00:22:22.110
JESSE HAINES: Have
you ever gigged?

00:22:22.110 --> 00:22:24.930
SARAH KESSLER: So it depends
which definition you're using.

00:22:24.930 --> 00:22:30.120
My book was technically a
supplemental income gig economy

00:22:30.120 --> 00:22:32.130
assignment.

00:22:32.130 --> 00:22:35.100
I also-- where I started
to get interested

00:22:35.100 --> 00:22:36.870
in the worker
perspective of this

00:22:36.870 --> 00:22:39.990
was about two years
after that startup

00:22:39.990 --> 00:22:41.640
blog, and hearing
all these pitches

00:22:41.640 --> 00:22:44.280
about how I'd be
working from the beach

00:22:44.280 --> 00:22:46.710
and doing what I love
whenever I want to.

00:22:46.710 --> 00:22:49.320
I pitched this self-serving
story to my editor

00:22:49.320 --> 00:22:51.270
at "Fast Company,"
like, hey, why don't I

00:22:51.270 --> 00:22:55.500
take a month off and do
this, and see how it goes?

00:22:55.500 --> 00:22:56.440
And they said yes.

00:22:56.440 --> 00:23:01.740
And so I spent a month
trying to beat minimum wage,

00:23:01.740 --> 00:23:03.300
signing up for kind of--

00:23:03.300 --> 00:23:06.660
I signed up for 30
or 40 platforms.

00:23:06.660 --> 00:23:10.560
Everything from virtual personal
assistants and TaskRabbits

00:23:10.560 --> 00:23:15.650
and dog walking and all of them.

00:23:15.650 --> 00:23:19.900
I had a class on Skillshare,
and I failed miserably.

00:23:19.900 --> 00:23:21.650
I couldn't-- I thought
it would be easier.

00:23:21.650 --> 00:23:22.980
JESSE HAINES: You weren't
a good dog walker?

00:23:22.980 --> 00:23:23.730
SARAH KESSLER: No.

00:23:23.730 --> 00:23:24.770
No one hired me.

00:23:24.770 --> 00:23:27.450
I guess I-- and I write
persuasively for a living,

00:23:27.450 --> 00:23:30.720
so I thought my profile
was pretty nice.

00:23:30.720 --> 00:23:31.920
I ended up--

00:23:31.920 --> 00:23:35.510
I dissolved someone's
LLC at the Harvard Club.

00:23:35.510 --> 00:23:40.182
I was in a proposal
dance flashmob.

00:23:40.182 --> 00:23:40.890
JESSE HAINES: OK.

00:23:40.890 --> 00:23:42.360
SARAH KESSLER: And I'm--

00:23:42.360 --> 00:23:45.390
you can definitely tell which
one is not trying to make it

00:23:45.390 --> 00:23:47.155
as a dancer in New York City.

00:23:47.155 --> 00:23:48.280
I'm like, oh, yeah, chasse.

00:23:48.280 --> 00:23:49.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:50.900 --> 00:23:51.720
And let's see.

00:23:51.720 --> 00:23:53.310
I did so many ridiculous things.

00:23:53.310 --> 00:23:57.170
I cleaned out people's closets
and tutored their kids.

00:23:57.170 --> 00:23:58.620
But it was really hard.

00:23:58.620 --> 00:24:00.030
And that was my
first realization

00:24:00.030 --> 00:24:04.440
of this is complicated for
me, college-educated person

00:24:04.440 --> 00:24:08.540
with actual full-time job
who's not relying on it.

00:24:08.540 --> 00:24:11.820
It must not be the same
story for everyone else.

00:24:11.820 --> 00:24:14.610
And that led to this
approach of trying

00:24:14.610 --> 00:24:20.910
to find different windows
of perspective and places

00:24:20.910 --> 00:24:24.170
in this bigger world that
we call the gig economy.

00:24:24.170 --> 00:24:25.515
JESSE HAINES: Fascinating.

00:24:25.515 --> 00:24:27.450
As I mentioned, I
think one of the things

00:24:27.450 --> 00:24:31.110
that I love about this book is
how you bring this human face

00:24:31.110 --> 00:24:34.170
to it-- the stories.

00:24:34.170 --> 00:24:36.600
Can you tell us a little
bit just around the writing

00:24:36.600 --> 00:24:37.110
process?

00:24:37.110 --> 00:24:38.970
How did you find these people?

00:24:38.970 --> 00:24:41.340
How did you piece
together these narratives?

00:24:41.340 --> 00:24:44.940
How did you choose who
to bring into the book,

00:24:44.940 --> 00:24:46.027
and who to leave out?

00:24:46.027 --> 00:24:46.860
SARAH KESSLER: Yeah.

00:24:46.860 --> 00:24:54.250
So that was a good year,
trying to figure out.

00:24:54.250 --> 00:24:56.790
And I was looking for
specific perspectives

00:24:56.790 --> 00:24:59.970
that I had data around that
showed the bigger picture,

00:24:59.970 --> 00:25:04.740
but I wanted to illustrate
by putting a face to it.

00:25:04.740 --> 00:25:07.230
I think that it's
important to tell stories

00:25:07.230 --> 00:25:10.890
that people can be engaged
in, and present people

00:25:10.890 --> 00:25:14.640
that they can care about,
instead of a white paper

00:25:14.640 --> 00:25:16.474
version.

00:25:16.474 --> 00:25:18.390
And so I was looking for
these certain people.

00:25:18.390 --> 00:25:20.910
Some of them, I came across
during my day-to-day reporting

00:25:20.910 --> 00:25:23.970
because I was still working as
a reporter at "Fast Company,"

00:25:23.970 --> 00:25:26.530
and I just stayed
in touch with them.

00:25:26.530 --> 00:25:32.370
Curtis, I met at a digital nomad
work meetup on his first day.

00:25:34.861 --> 00:25:36.360
And then, there
were a lot of people

00:25:36.360 --> 00:25:39.420
who I began relationships
with, thinking that they might

00:25:39.420 --> 00:25:41.710
be people I'd include in the
book, who I didn't end up

00:25:41.710 --> 00:25:44.460
including, for various reasons.

00:25:44.460 --> 00:25:46.880
Most of the people in the
book were seeking attention

00:25:46.880 --> 00:25:49.410
for one reason or another.

00:25:49.410 --> 00:25:53.270
Some people, their lives became
such that they really were not,

00:25:53.270 --> 00:26:00.087
and I, for the most
part, respected that.

00:26:00.087 --> 00:26:00.670
But it's hard.

00:26:00.670 --> 00:26:02.400
You have to spend--

00:26:02.400 --> 00:26:05.030
to write about
