Thank you very much.

00:26:31.550 --> 00:26:34.540
You touched quite a bit
on regulation and the lack

00:26:34.540 --> 00:26:36.137
of regulation, really.

00:26:36.137 --> 00:26:37.720
Some of the things
that you mentioned,

00:26:37.720 --> 00:26:39.640
like portable health
care benefits,

00:26:39.640 --> 00:26:41.560
seem very US-specific.

00:26:41.560 --> 00:26:44.650
I'm wondering if you've got
any insights into how countries

00:26:44.650 --> 00:26:47.110
abroad are tackling this
because I feel like this

00:26:47.110 --> 00:26:48.887
is an issue that a lot
of different places

00:26:48.887 --> 00:26:51.030
are grappling with.

00:26:51.030 --> 00:26:52.540
SARAH KESSLER: So
various things.

00:26:52.540 --> 00:26:59.580
Some countries in-between
classification.

00:26:59.580 --> 00:27:02.020
So in the US, you can either
be an independent contractor,

00:27:02.020 --> 00:27:03.250
you can be an employee.

00:27:03.250 --> 00:27:04.690
If you're an employee,
you have all the rights

00:27:04.690 --> 00:27:06.040
and all the benefits,
and your company

00:27:06.040 --> 00:27:07.130
has to pay all the money.

00:27:07.130 --> 00:27:08.902
And if you're an
independent contractor,

00:27:08.902 --> 00:27:11.110
you have none of the rights
and none of the benefits,

00:27:11.110 --> 00:27:14.050
and your company just
has to pay you whatever

00:27:14.050 --> 00:27:16.840
they said your wage would be.

00:27:16.840 --> 00:27:18.790
Some companies have an
in-between category,

00:27:18.790 --> 00:27:23.000
where if you're a
dependent contractor,

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:25.160
you have some rights.

00:27:25.160 --> 00:27:27.730
So there's an in-between.

00:27:27.730 --> 00:27:30.550
Some countries in
Africa, the gig economy

00:27:30.550 --> 00:27:31.910
is just the economy.

00:27:31.910 --> 00:27:36.040
Everybody's an entrepreneur, so
this whole discussion probably

00:27:36.040 --> 00:27:36.820
seems absurd.

00:27:39.670 --> 00:27:42.230
And then, some companies
have taken a more active role

00:27:42.230 --> 00:27:44.910
in regulating--

00:27:44.910 --> 00:27:47.890
saying certain
apps can't be here,

00:27:47.890 --> 00:27:51.160
or you have to set
a minimum wage.

00:27:51.160 --> 00:27:55.270
Actually, New York just set a
minimum wage for Uber drivers.

00:27:55.270 --> 00:27:56.620
It's not exactly a minimum wage.

00:27:56.620 --> 00:28:00.280
It's an equation of
what they have to make.

00:28:00.280 --> 00:28:02.600
And that's about
all I have for that.

00:28:05.522 --> 00:28:07.486
AUDIENCE: What amount
of responsibility

00:28:07.486 --> 00:28:12.092
do the companies that
create these gig [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:12.092 --> 00:28:18.830
feel they have to
their freelancers?

00:28:18.830 --> 00:28:20.460
I think Uber gets--

00:28:20.460 --> 00:28:22.730
which is the biggest example--

00:28:22.730 --> 00:28:24.320
has a lot of
language about this.

00:28:24.320 --> 00:28:26.775
But what about the people
who just start something?

00:28:26.775 --> 00:28:30.051
Do they just think, OK, if
we build it, they will come,

00:28:30.051 --> 00:28:31.550
and we don't have
to worry about it?

00:28:31.550 --> 00:28:34.642
Or do they-- what's the
landscape like there?

00:28:34.642 --> 00:28:36.350
SARAH KESSLER: How
much should they have,

00:28:36.350 --> 00:28:38.180
or how much do they think
that they should have?

00:28:38.180 --> 00:28:39.830
AUDIENCE: How much do you
think they should have,

00:28:39.830 --> 00:28:42.212
in terms just of where
there are some good examples

00:28:42.212 --> 00:28:43.571
of good guys, bad guys.

00:28:43.571 --> 00:28:44.320
SARAH KESSLER: OK.

00:28:44.320 --> 00:28:46.349
AUDIENCE: What's
your thought on that?

00:28:46.349 --> 00:28:48.140
SARAH KESSLER: I would
say, a lot of times,

00:28:48.140 --> 00:28:52.350
I think that it's
somewhat of a--

00:28:52.350 --> 00:28:54.160
it gets away from
them, in some way.

00:28:54.160 --> 00:28:58.130
They don't understand the effect
that this would have on people,

00:28:58.130 --> 00:29:02.360
or that even if it's great to
be a freelancer as a software

00:29:02.360 --> 00:29:04.760
programmer, it might
be different to be

00:29:04.760 --> 00:29:08.870
a freelance line
cook or whatever.

00:29:08.870 --> 00:29:10.910
I do think that
they're operating

00:29:10.910 --> 00:29:14.180
in a system that was
fundamentally not

00:29:14.180 --> 00:29:17.870
built for what they're doing.

00:29:17.870 --> 00:29:20.990
And that policy allows--

00:29:20.990 --> 00:29:27.680
the way policy is written allows
for this in-between management.

00:29:27.680 --> 00:29:30.290
And if things are
going to make--

00:29:30.290 --> 00:29:33.140
if we're going to make big
changes that fix this problem,

00:29:33.140 --> 00:29:37.580
it needs to be a policy-driven
thing, and not a new app,

00:29:37.580 --> 00:29:39.920
or a new way to buy
workers compensation

00:29:39.920 --> 00:29:43.280
insurance for yourself because
your company has no obligation

00:29:43.280 --> 00:29:44.210
to provide it to you.

00:29:47.210 --> 00:29:51.920
And so I think individual
companies can really only--

00:29:51.920 --> 00:29:54.770
they should be good actors
towards their own ecosystem,

00:29:54.770 --> 00:29:57.830
but can't totally
fix all the problems.

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:04.000
AUDIENCE: From the stories
that you covered, to me,

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:06.850
there seemed like there
is this idea of they're

00:30:06.850 --> 00:30:10.900
in survival mode, just
trying to make it day by day,

00:30:10.900 --> 00:30:12.610
and figure out how--

00:30:12.610 --> 00:30:17.780
solving short-term
life planning.

00:30:17.780 --> 00:30:20.540
Do you get a sense that any of
the people that you followed

00:30:20.540 --> 00:30:23.600
had a long-term perspective
of where they envisioned

00:30:23.600 --> 00:30:27.320
themselves in 10 years,
20 years where they

00:30:27.320 --> 00:30:29.000
worried some about the future?

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:31.760
To me, that just seems like
a little bit of the backlash

00:30:31.760 --> 00:30:36.297
of this [INAUDIBLE] framework.

00:30:36.297 --> 00:30:38.380
SARAH KESSLER: I'd say,
in the hierarchy of needs,

00:30:38.380 --> 00:30:41.847
if you're there because
this is what you need to do,

00:30:41.847 --> 00:30:43.430
then you think about
your money first,

00:30:43.430 --> 00:30:45.330
and health insurance
only becomes a problem

00:30:45.330 --> 00:30:47.430
when you get in a car accident.

00:30:47.430 --> 00:30:50.430
And then it becomes
a big problem.

00:30:50.430 --> 00:30:53.040
But there were people who--

00:30:53.040 --> 00:30:58.680
the Uber driver who I follow
in the book, Abe, he had,

00:30:58.680 --> 00:31:04.230
for a long time, been obsessed
with becoming a millionaire,

00:31:04.230 --> 00:31:06.450
and falling for all these
get-rich-quick schemes,

00:31:06.450 --> 00:31:07.617
which he kind of--

00:31:07.617 --> 00:31:10.200
when Uber made this pitch, like,
you can be your own business,

00:31:10.200 --> 00:31:16.350
and you can join this echelon
of entrepreneurs, he signed up.

00:31:16.350 --> 00:31:18.150
And yeah, today,
he still believes

00:31:18.150 --> 00:31:21.840
he's going to be a
millionaire, which

00:31:21.840 --> 00:31:24.480
I found really interesting.

00:31:24.480 --> 00:31:31.250
Because if you look
at mobility in the US,

00:31:31.250 --> 00:31:35.180
and think about why people
join get-rich-quick schemes,

00:31:35.180 --> 00:31:36.620
there's really--

00:31:36.620 --> 00:31:39.512
it doesn't feel like if
you work hard, and you--

00:31:39.512 --> 00:31:40.970
if you're not coming
from anywhere,

00:31:40.970 --> 00:31:42.636
that you're actually
going to get ahead.

00:31:42.636 --> 00:31:44.300
It feels like you need that.

00:31:44.300 --> 00:31:46.070
So that was an
interesting thing.

00:31:46.070 --> 00:31:48.210
And then, the people
who are there by choice,

00:31:48.210 --> 00:31:52.430
I think it is a investment in
their lifestyle and future,

00:31:52.430 --> 00:31:54.152
and where they want to be.

00:31:54.152 --> 00:31:55.610
AUDIENCE: In all
of the people that

00:31:55.610 --> 00:31:57.530
you followed in your
years of research,

00:31:57.530 --> 00:32:02.210
did you come across any
particular tools that

00:32:02.210 --> 00:32:05.642
are actually helping [INAUDIBLE]
really good resources that you

00:32:05.642 --> 00:32:08.060
came-- that you
encountered over and over?

00:32:08.060 --> 00:32:11.290
Whether it's around health
care, or retirement planning,

00:32:11.290 --> 00:32:15.600
or non-payment protections
or anything like that?

00:32:15.600 --> 00:32:19.080
The thing about the gig economy
is that it's not one industry.

00:32:19.080 --> 00:32:20.670
It's not one job type.

00:32:20.670 --> 00:32:23.100
So information is
very fragmented,

00:32:23.100 --> 00:32:26.000
and even for
freelancers and giggers,

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:27.970
it's really hard to
find this information.

00:32:27.970 --> 00:32:32.190
So I'm just wondering if you
found any companies, startups,

00:32:32.190 --> 00:32:35.879
or tools out there that
stood out for [INAUDIBLE]..

00:32:35.879 --> 00:32:38.170
SARAH KESSLER: I came across
a lot of interesting ones,

00:32:38.170 --> 00:32:41.770
but I never came across one
that people who are working

00:32:41.770 --> 00:32:43.690
knew about and told me about.

00:32:43.690 --> 00:32:45.580
So I came across a lot
of interesting ideas,

00:32:45.580 --> 00:32:48.790
but it didn't seem like
they were being really

00:32:48.790 --> 00:32:50.530
embraced or used.

00:32:50.530 --> 00:32:54.460
One interesting idea are savings
tools, where a big problem

00:32:54.460 --> 00:32:55.630
is your income is variable.

00:32:55.630 --> 00:32:59.230
You don't know how much money
you're going to make next week.

00:32:59.230 --> 00:33:01.960
So they take a bit-- if
you're having a good week,

00:33:01.960 --> 00:33:04.900
they take a bit of your
income, and save it.

00:33:04.900 --> 00:33:08.030
And then, if you're having a bad
week, they pay it back to you.

00:33:08.030 --> 00:33:11.200
So it's an attempt of
evening out the uncertainty

00:33:11.200 --> 00:33:12.580
in the income.

00:33:15.275 --> 00:33:19.460
But I didn't actually find
anybody who was using it.

00:33:19.460 --> 00:33:21.340
There's attempts to
break down insurance

00:33:21.340 --> 00:33:25.000
to make it easier to
buy as a freelancer.

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:30.790
But again, in the hierarchy
of immediate needs,

00:33:30.790 --> 00:33:35.620
maybe that's not first on your
mind if you're a freelancer.

00:33:35.620 --> 00:33:39.290
AUDIENCE: When it comes to
[INAUDIBLE],, in general,

00:33:39.290 --> 00:33:41.760
if we look at it
