00:35:58.817 --> 00:35:59.650
SARAH KESSLER: Yeah.

00:35:59.650 --> 00:36:01.210
I think I see--

00:36:01.210 --> 00:36:05.680
I see-- there's, on the one
hand, the big trend, which is--

00:36:05.680 --> 00:36:10.820
the decades' long trend of
outsourcing, which is, I

00:36:10.820 --> 00:36:12.070
don't want to hire my janitor.

00:36:12.070 --> 00:36:14.260
I want to hire the company
that provides my janitor.

00:36:14.260 --> 00:36:20.380
Or I don't want to hire people
directly that work in my field.

00:36:20.380 --> 00:36:24.611
I'm going to hire the temp
workers to work in my field.

00:36:24.611 --> 00:36:26.860
And I think if you look at
some of these basic things,

00:36:26.860 --> 00:36:27.670
you'll find it.

00:36:27.670 --> 00:36:30.700
But it's just what we're
paying attention to is Uber

00:36:30.700 --> 00:36:33.760
and this very extreme
version of that, which

00:36:33.760 --> 00:36:36.850
is I'm employing
you for, literally,

00:36:36.850 --> 00:36:39.750
when I get in your car
to when I leave your car.

00:36:39.750 --> 00:36:43.592
And so it's almost
a version of that.

00:36:43.592 --> 00:36:44.490
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:36:44.490 --> 00:36:47.760
One of the shifts that
the gig economy brought

00:36:47.760 --> 00:36:52.430
is that workers no longer get
training as part of their jobs.

00:36:52.430 --> 00:36:55.800
Did you find-- how do you
find these folks reflect

00:36:55.800 --> 00:36:59.690
on the upskilling that they
have to do all the time?

00:36:59.690 --> 00:37:02.400
Is this something they
pursue on their own?

00:37:02.400 --> 00:37:05.018
Do they just not pursue jobs
they're unqualified for?

00:37:05.018 --> 00:37:07.614
How does education connect
to this very different--

00:37:07.614 --> 00:37:09.280
SARAH KESSLER: Yeah,
that's interesting.

00:37:09.280 --> 00:37:13.990
Because for some people, I
think it is an upskilling.

00:37:13.990 --> 00:37:18.370
They use it to go build a resume
by doing these freelance jobs.

00:37:18.370 --> 00:37:22.930
But on the other hand,
there's other types of work.

00:37:22.930 --> 00:37:24.940
I don't know who
said it's not a--

00:37:24.940 --> 00:37:25.930
it's not a sector.

00:37:25.930 --> 00:37:28.510
It's a management strategy
is how I think of it.

00:37:28.510 --> 00:37:32.310
So it could be any kind of work.

00:37:32.310 --> 00:37:35.140
So some people use it
as an upskilling thing.

00:37:35.140 --> 00:37:37.450
But then there are others,
where there's no opportunity

00:37:37.450 --> 00:37:38.800
to really learn something new.

00:37:38.800 --> 00:37:40.667
And if you're not
an employee that

00:37:40.667 --> 00:37:42.250
belongs to the
company, what incentive

00:37:42.250 --> 00:37:45.190
do they have to teach
you how to do anything

00:37:45.190 --> 00:37:47.360
you don't already
know how to do?

00:37:47.360 --> 00:37:51.430
I think you're seeing
a lot of companies

00:37:51.430 --> 00:37:55.120
try to solve this problem by
offering free online classes,

00:37:55.120 --> 00:38:05.170
or I think Salesforce,
LinkedIn, Google, and a Fiverr,

00:38:05.170 --> 00:38:10.810
like this freelance platform,
they all offer online skills.

00:38:10.810 --> 00:38:12.670
You can take this
class and you can show

00:38:12.670 --> 00:38:14.669
that you have this new skill.

00:38:14.669 --> 00:38:16.960
So the evolution of that, I
think, will be interesting.

00:38:16.960 --> 00:38:19.329
And I don't know what
will happen to it.

00:38:19.329 --> 00:38:21.370
JESSE HAINES: And I think
another dimension to it

00:38:21.370 --> 00:38:24.580
is the need for
upskilling, and then

00:38:24.580 --> 00:38:27.460
the gig economy allowing
you to have that flexibility

00:38:27.460 --> 00:38:30.850
to work so that you
can go to school

00:38:30.850 --> 00:38:33.680
