looking for other options,

00:39:16.180 --> 00:39:19.300
or is it the flexibility
is giving them

00:39:19.300 --> 00:39:21.895
enough value that it offsets
the fact that they're not

00:39:21.895 --> 00:39:22.812
making a lot of money?

00:39:22.812 --> 00:39:24.436
SARAH KESSLER: I
think one thing that's

00:39:24.436 --> 00:39:27.430
interesting about the data
is a large portion of people

00:39:27.430 --> 00:39:31.600
are doing this part-time,
or on a supplemental basis,

00:39:31.600 --> 00:39:35.470
which, to me, suggests
unemployment is very low.

00:39:35.470 --> 00:39:38.680
But what does the quality
of those jobs look like?

00:39:38.680 --> 00:39:43.360
And can people actually
make ends meet on a job,

00:39:43.360 --> 00:39:47.420
or do they have to do more?

00:39:47.420 --> 00:39:50.830
I think it's too
soon to see data

00:39:50.830 --> 00:39:52.930
about whether now that
unemployment is so low,

00:39:52.930 --> 00:39:55.210
will fewer people
be freelancers?

00:39:55.210 --> 00:39:57.975
Will fewer people be doing this?

00:39:57.975 --> 00:39:59.350
But it's an
interesting question.

00:39:59.350 --> 00:40:01.600
JESSE HAINES: I will throw
in that, as I was preparing

00:40:01.600 --> 00:40:04.180
for this talk, I came across
this stat, which I almost

00:40:04.180 --> 00:40:04.900
couldn't believe.

00:40:04.900 --> 00:40:07.840
And I'm curious to
get your take on it.

00:40:07.840 --> 00:40:10.600
A recent survey commissioned
by the online freelancing

00:40:10.600 --> 00:40:13.690
platform, Upwork and
the Freelancers Union

00:40:13.690 --> 00:40:15.730
shows that the freelance
workforce is growing

00:40:15.730 --> 00:40:18.620
three times faster than
the overall US workforce,

00:40:18.620 --> 00:40:21.250
and that the majority of people
will be working independently

00:40:21.250 --> 00:40:25.847
by 2027, which is right
around the corner.

00:40:25.847 --> 00:40:26.680
SARAH KESSLER: Yeah.

00:40:26.680 --> 00:40:29.110
There's so much data.

00:40:29.110 --> 00:40:31.099
It's so hard to quantify this.

00:40:31.099 --> 00:40:31.890
JESSE HAINES: Yeah.

00:40:35.617 --> 00:40:37.450
SARAH KESSLER: Different
government agencies

00:40:37.450 --> 00:40:40.840
have suggested that the number
of freelancers in the US

00:40:40.840 --> 00:40:44.314
is anywhere between 10% to 40%.

00:40:44.314 --> 00:40:45.730
JESSE HAINES:
That's a huge delta.

00:40:45.730 --> 00:40:47.500
SARAH KESSLER: So
Freelancers Union

00:40:47.500 --> 00:40:51.770
is asking, have you done
freelance work this year,

00:40:51.770 --> 00:40:53.910
which is a very different
question than the BLS

00:40:53.910 --> 00:40:56.350
survey, which asks,
was your main job

00:40:56.350 --> 00:40:59.940
this week independent
contractor work?

00:40:59.940 --> 00:41:02.380
To which the person on the
other end of the phone says,

00:41:02.380 --> 00:41:03.700
what's a main job?

00:41:03.700 --> 00:41:05.170
What's an independent
contractor?

00:41:05.170 --> 00:41:08.102
I don't know if I'm classified
as an independent contractor.

00:41:08.102 --> 00:41:09.560
Can I get you to
hang up the phone?

00:41:09.560 --> 00:41:10.270
Sure.

00:41:10.270 --> 00:41:10.912
Yes, fine.

00:41:10.912 --> 00:41:11.620
That's what I am.

00:41:11.620 --> 00:41:14.260
Or no, I'm not.

00:41:14.260 --> 00:41:15.850
So it's hard to tell.

00:41:18.760 --> 00:41:20.800
People fight about this a lot.

00:41:20.800 --> 00:41:22.360
What is the percentage?

00:41:22.360 --> 00:41:24.880
And I think it's almost
a distracting question.

00:41:24.880 --> 00:41:27.160
JESSE HAINES: Yeah.

00:41:27.160 --> 00:41:28.780
So I think we're
going to wrap up.

00:41:28.780 --> 00:41:33.670
I'd love to just end
on, beyond the book,

00:41:33.670 --> 00:41:37.060
as you've been covering
the future of work, what

00:41:37.060 --> 00:41:43.150
are some other interesting
trends that you see,

00:41:43.150 --> 00:41:45.310
or other sort of
emerging hot topics

00:41:45.310 --> 00:41:49.137
in this interesting conversation
about the future of work?

00:41:49.137 --> 00:41:49.970
SARAH KESSLER: Yeah.

00:41:49.970 --> 00:41:51.610
So we don't know, because
it's in the future, what

00:41:51.610 --> 00:41:52.430
will happen.

00:41:52.430 --> 00:41:59.070
But I think that how will
technology change work

00:41:59.070 --> 00:42:02.170
is an interesting question,
just like it was 100 years ago,

00:42:02.170 --> 00:42:06.050
and it will continue to be.

00:42:06.050 --> 00:42:11.340
And I think the culture of
even not being in the office

00:42:11.340 --> 00:42:13.410
is really interesting.

00:42:13.410 --> 00:42:16.160
Maybe it will all start
to spread out more.

00:42:16.160 --> 00:42:19.290
But I don't have a big thesis
about, the future of work

00:42:19.290 --> 00:42:22.320
is chat bots or
anything like that.

00:42:22.320 --> 00:42:22.820
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:22.820 --> 00:42:25.110
JESSE HAINES: Anything
that, when you were writing

00:42:25.110 --> 00:42:28.279
this book, surprised you?

00:42:28.279 --> 00:42:29.820
SARAH KESSLER: I
think the thing that

00:42:29.820 --> 00:42:36.030
surprised me is I started out
with, OK, Silicon Valley had

00:42:36.030 --> 00:42:41.142
this idea, and made
this guess, or promise,

00:42:41.142 --> 00:42:42.100
about what it would be.

00:42:42.100 --> 00:42:43.810
What does that look like?

00:42:43.810 --> 00:42:46.920
And then that-- just
how big that question

00:42:46.920 --> 00:42:49.210
got, to the point
where you're like, OK.

00:42:49.210 --> 00:42:52.020
Well, then, there's
this bigger trend

00:42:52.020 --> 00:42:54.150
of work moving this
way, in general,

00:42:54.150 --> 00:42:56.010
and risk moving to
workers, in general.

00:42:56.010 --> 00:42:58.260
And then, the history of
work and the Industrial

00:42:58.260 --> 00:43:02.580
Revolution, and just how much
was packed into this one story

00:43:02.580 --> 00:43:05.400
about apps like
Uber, and how much

00:43:05.400 --> 00:43:08.040
it touches other
than Uber, which

00:43:08.040 --> 00:43:09.180
is what we all talk about.

00:43:09.180 --> 00:43:11.388
Which, in a way, is great
because it brings attention

00:43:11.388 --> 00:43:13.567
to this issue, but it's
much bigger than that.

00:43:13.567 --> 00:43:14.400
JESSE HAINES: Great.

00:43:14.400 --> 00:43:15.240
SARAH KESSLER: Yeah.

00:43:15.240 --> 00:43:16.650
JESSE HAINES: Well, if
you guys can join me

00:43:16.650 --> 00:43:19.260
in thanking Sarah Kessler
for being with us here today.

00:43:19.260 --> 00:43:22.610
[APPLAUSE]

